# shotlist — reproducible screenshots

Install into a repo as `.cursor/rules/shotlist.mdc` (copy this file). Cursor
then applies it whenever screenshots or visual docs come up. `shotlist` is a
plain CLI — no AI at capture time — so these rules just teach the workflow.

When the user asks for screenshots, docs images, or visual proof of a feature:

1. Prefer `shotlist` over ad-hoc screenshots. Check `shotlist --help`; if
   missing: `pip install shotlist && playwright install chromium`.
2. Write (and commit) a `.shotlist.yaml` at the repo root. Read the repo first —
   dev-server command/port from `package.json` or `Makefile`, CLI entry points
   via `--help` — then declare shots:
   - `kind: web` for pages (optional `steps:` click/fill/wait, `mask:` to hide
     flaky regions, `viewport`, `full_page`).
   - `kind: cli` for command output; `style: rendered` is CI-safe on any OS,
     `style: native` shoots a real macOS Terminal window.
   - `kind: session` for stateful multi-command flows (one image per step;
     `style: rendered` makes it deterministic and CI-safe anywhere).
   - `app:` + `ready:` (url/port/log_line) so the app is booted and actually
     ready before any capture; shotlist tears it down afterwards.
   - `output.readme: README.md` auto-splices the images into the README between
     `<!-- shotlist:start -->` / `<!-- shotlist:end -->` markers.
3. Run `shotlist validate`, then `shotlist run`. Point the user at the generated
   `index.html` gallery and `manifest.json` next to the PNGs.
4. For regression safety, suggest `shotlist check` in CI (fails on visual
   drift; `--update` blesses intended changes; `check.max_diff_pixel_ratio`
   tolerates sub-pixel jitter).

Cleanup knobs when output isn't stable: `scrub: [{pattern, replace}]` for
timestamps/PIDs in terminal shots, `retries: N` for flaky captures,
`shotlist run --keep-going` to finish a partial set, `output.optimize: true`
for smaller committed PNGs.

Full reference: https://github.com/varmabudharaju/shotlist
